"n.竪琴；v.喋喋不休地说或写 【考】 horn : blow / harp : pluck(吹喇叭/拔竪琴) n. 竪琴 【记】hard, p: harp一玩就是几个小时, P都hard了读: 害怕－你妈突然让你学harp, 你会感到很害怕想玩harp需要hard努力 【类】horn: blow = harp: pluck 吹喇叭 = 拔竪琴 【记】音：画谱，划谱，划五线谱时，需要竪琴边找音边弹；happy 高兴，一高兴就想唱歌，用竪琴来伴奏； harp (n.)  Old English hearpe, from Proto-Germanic *harpon- (cognates: Old Saxon harpa ""instrument of torture;"" Old Norse harpa, Dutch harp, Old High German harpfa, German Harfe ""harp"") of uncertain origin. Late Latin harpa, source of words in some Romanic languages, is a borrowing from Germanic. Meaning ""harmonica"" is from 1887, short for mouth-harp. The harp seal (1784) is so called for the harp-shaped markings on its back. harp (v.)  Old English hearpian; see harp (n.). Cognate with Middle Dutch, Dutch harpen, Middle High German harpfen, German harfen. Figurative sense of ""talk overmuch"" (about something) first recorded mid-15c., originally to harp upon one string. Related: Harped; harping."
